04459nam a22005895i 9780822390343DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223903437 a10.1515/97808223903432doi  a(DE-B1597)554472  a(OCoLC)1224278619  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ799.I52bB38 2007 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aBaulch, Emma, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Scenes :bReggae, Punk, and Death Metal in 1990s Bali /cEmma Baulch. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b12 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tNote on Spelling, Names -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Messy Decay -- t2. Gesturing Elsewhere -- t3. Reggae Borderzones, Reggae Graveyards -- t4. Punk's Beginnings -- t5. Grounding Punk -- t6. Metal Blossoms -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1996, Emma Baulch went to live in Bali to do research on youth culture. Her chats with young people led her to an enormously popular regular outdoor show dominated by local reggae, punk, and death metal bands. In this rich ethnography, she takes readers inside each scene: hanging out in the death metal scene among unemployed university graduates clad in black T-shirts and ragged jeans; in the punk scene among young men sporting mohawks, leather jackets, and hefty jackboots; and among the remnants of the local reggae scene in Kuta Beach, the island's most renowned tourist area. Baulch tracks how each music scene arrived and grew in Bali, looking at such influences as the global extreme metal underground, MTV Asia, and the internationalization of Indonesia's music industry.Making Scenes is an exploration of the subtle politics of identity that took place within and among these scenes throughout the course of the 1990s. Participants in the different scenes often explained their interest in death metal, punk, or reggae in relation to broader ideas about what it meant to be Balinese, which reflected views about Bali's tourism industry and the cultural dominance of Jakarta, Indonesia's capital and largest city. Through dance, dress, claims to public spaces, and onstage performances, participants and enthusiasts reworked "Balinese-ness" by synthesizing global media, ideas of national belonging, and local identity politics. Making Scenes chronicles the creation of subcultures at a historical moment when media globalization and the gradual demise of the authoritarian Suharto regime coincided with revitalized, essentialist formulations of the Balinese self.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aDeath metal (Music)xSocial aspectszIndonesiazBali Island. 0aGroup identityzIndonesiazBali Island. 0aPunk rock musicxSocial aspectszIndonesiazBali Island. 0aReggae musicxSocial aspectszIndonesiazBali Island. 0aSubculturezIndonesiazBali Island. 0aYouthzIndonesiazBali (Province)xSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390343zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390343423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390343.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles